				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Not sure what role I'm supposed to be filling<a name="57110"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Aug 17 04 12:03 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Everyone pretty much nailed it here. Right now you're in a lull, pun intended, and all of us go through it around lvl 55-56, things slow down and the class dynamics shift. Like the others said, you can't expect your role to be as noticeable quite yet, unless you're pulling. Being a good puller in LDoNs is really empowering and something I encourage all bards to strive for, it can really change the way you look at our class, but don't expect the xp to pour in. Check out the forum on lvls 51-60, there are Countless threads from people about the crawl from 55-60 and how much it sucks, you're experienceing a part of this. I've given a lot of advice in many threads about how to handle this, but my biggest reccommendation is, get your epic. Work on it while you /lfg and put a message in your /lfg window along the lines of &quot;Will pull for food&quot; or something catchy and try to take on as many LDoNs as you can. I really advise doing EF, the pulling is fun and you can learn a lot about how to target semi-hidden mobs and how to inch up to low visibility pulls. It also doesn't hurt that the armor in EF is awesome, second only to Tak, which is much more difficult imho, also look at the fact that Call of the Muse comes from EF and it's really a no brainer. If you want good xp in LDoN you pretty much need to be the lowest lvl in the group, which can also teach you a thing or two because you won't be able to mezz/charm a good deal of the mobs if you're lower than the others. Keep that Deftdance hotkey ready! I stopped soloing at 56 almost all together and started doing LDoNs almost full time, it's a huge ego boost when you get it right and it's a huge reality check when you screw it up. Lots of folks will tell you not to do pickup groups, but it's almost unavoidable so just try to have patience with people and take charge, you'll discover that you can do a lot more than you give yourself credit for, especially when you're the glue holding a rag tag group together. Keep at it man, this is the point where a lot of folks lose hope and make alts, don't do it! Get those blue notes going and try as hard as you can to meet as many people as possible, if it wasn't for the people I would have quit this game years ago. 
<br />
don't give up!
<br />
</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
