				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Not sure what role I'm supposed to be filling<a name="57435"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Aug 18 04 11:35 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>In response to an earlier post on alts:
<br />

<br />
PLAY THEM!!! By all means, play them. My bard started out as an alt to my 55 (at the time) ranger. My ranger is now 57 and naked except for nodrop gear. I loved my bard so much I couldnt stop playing him until he hit 65. Now and again as I leveled my bard I would take time out to play an alt. (BTW, bard went 34-65 in 2 months, only playing after work/weekends) Doing this does two things: it prevents you from getting burnt out, and it gives you an insight into other classes. I find I am much more understanding of clerics after having played my wifes cleric off and on level 1-65. Playing other classes will let you know: 1-you are more uber then you first suspected, 2-you are much better at filling an empty spot then ANY other class PERIOD, 3-if you play an alt and group with a competently played bard, you will notice how very much that bard does for you and your efficiency as a group. I think you are getting too caught up in your weaknesses and not focusing on your skills. You see a ranger and ask: &quot;Why can't I do that dps?&quot; or at a chanter and say: &quot;Wish I could charm that mob for that long.&quot; What you don't know is the chanter looks at you and thinks: &quot;Wish I could run that fast and survive being hit more than 3 times&quot;, and the Ranger is thinking: &quot;I wish I could mez that mob and regen mana for the group and slow the mob and haste the group.... or be WANTED IN A GROUP.&quot; 
<br />

<br />
I can say, having played a mid-50's ranger, that it is nigh-impossible to find a group with a ranger unless it is with a group of friends, or you form the group yourself.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
